menu "SPI NAND Flash configuration"

    config NAND_FLASH_VERIFY_WRITE
        bool "Verify SPI NAND flash writes"
        default n
        help
            If this option is enabled, any time SPI NAND flash is written then the data will be read
            back and verified. This can catch hardware problems with SPI NAND flash, or flash which
            was not erased before verification.

    config NAND_PAGE_REGISTER_CACHE
        bool "Skip READ PAGE on repeated access to the same page"
        default n
        help
            The NAND chip holds one page in its internal register.  When this
            option is enabled, the driver remembers which page is currently
            loaded and skips the redundant READ PAGE command (~25–100 µs)
            on back-to-back reads of the same page.  The tracking is reset
            automatically after every program or erase.

            Disable to force a fresh READ PAGE on every read — useful for
            measuring baseline read latency without this optimisation.

    config NAND_FLASH_ENABLE_BDL
        bool "Enable Block Device Layer (BDL) support"
        depends on IDF_INIT_VERSION >= "6.0"
        default n
        help
            Enable Block Device Layer (BDL) support for SPI NAND Flash. This provides:
            - Standard esp_blockdev_t interface for layered architecture
            - Flash Block Device Layer (raw NAND flash access)
            - Wear-Leveling Block Device Layer (logical sector access with wear leveling)
            - Advanced layered API (spi_nand_flash_init_with_layers)
            When disabled, only the legacy API is available.
            When enabled, the legacy spi_nand_flash_init_device() is not available (returns
            ESP_ERR_NOT_SUPPORTED). Use spi_nand_flash_init_with_layers().

            Note: This option requires ESP-IDF >= 6.0 (esp_blockdev component).
            Enabling this on ESP-IDF < 6.0 will result in a build error.

    config DHARA_META_CACHE_SLOTS
        int "Metadata checkpoint-page cache slots (0 = disabled)"
        range 0 8
        default 0
        help
            Number of full NAND pages cached in internal DRAM to accelerate
            repeated metadata reads from the same checkpoint group. Each slot
            holds one page (typically 2048 bytes) in DMA-aligned internal DRAM.
            Total cost: SLOTS x page_size bytes.
            Set 0 to disable (no RAM overhead, original behaviour).
            Recommended value TODO for targets with spare RAM.

    config DHARA_MAP_PATH_CACHE
        bool "Enable trace_path sequential locality cache"
        default n
        help
            When enabled, dhara_map caches the last successful read-only
            trace_path traversal (136 bytes in struct dhara_map). Consecutive
            sector lookups that share a common radix-tree prefix skip the
            already-known levels entirely, reducing dhara_journal_read_meta
            calls by up to 31 of 32 for sequential sector access patterns.
            Set to false to disable (no RAM overhead, original behaviour).

    config NAND_ENABLE_STATS
        bool "Host test statistics enabled"
        depends on IDF_TARGET_LINUX
        default n
        help
            This option enables gathering host test statistics and SPI NAND flash wear levelling simulation.

    config NAND_FLASH_PROG_PAGE_RELIEF
        bool "Pre-program read: request Dhara page relief on high correctable ECC"
        default n
        help
            After the mandatory pre-program page read, if the NAND reports correctable ECC at or above
            NAND_FLASH_PROG_PAGE_RELIEF_MIN_ECC, nand_prog returns ESP_ERR_FLASH_BASE + DHARA_E_PAGE_RELIEF.
            The Dhara journal consumes a filler metadata slot and uses the next physical page without
            marking the block bad. Uncorrectable ECC still fails the operation with ESP_FAIL.

    config NAND_FLASH_PROG_PAGE_RELIEF_MIN_ECC
        int "Minimum nand_ecc_status_t value to trigger page relief (inclusive)"
        depends on NAND_FLASH_PROG_PAGE_RELIEF
        range 1 7
        default 3
        help
            Compared against ecc_corrected_bits_status after the pre-read (see nand_ecc_status_t).
            Typical values: 1 = NAND_ECC_1_TO_3_BITS_CORRECTED, 3 = NAND_ECC_4_TO_6_BITS_CORRECTED.

    config NAND_FLASH_FAULT_SIM
        bool "Enable NAND fault-injection simulator (for linux target ftl_eval app)"
        depends on IDF_TARGET_LINUX
        default n
        help
            When enabled, nand_fault_sim.c replaces nand_impl_linux.c at link time.
            The fault simulator implements the same nand_impl interface and supports
            configurable fault injection: factory bad blocks, erase/program wear-out,
            retention failure, per-operation probabilistic failures, power-loss crash
            with torn writes, and ECC read-disturb simulation.
            Linux target only. Zero impact on firmware builds.
            Used by the ftl_eval evaluation app.

endmenu
